{"title_page": "2A self-cleaving peptides", "text_new": "[[File:2A peptide Working Mechanism.jpg|thumb|An illustration of 2A peptide function: when the [[Coding DNA sequence|CDS]] of a 2A peptide is inserted between two CDSs of protein, the peptide will be cleaved into two proteins folding independently.]]\n'''2A self-cleaving peptides''', or '''2A peptides''', is a class of 18\u201322 [[amino acid|aa]]-long peptides, which can induce the cleaving of the [[recombinant protein]] in cell. 2A peptides are derived from the 2A region in the [[genome]] of [[virus]]es.<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Liu|first1=Ziqing|last2=Chen|first2=Olivia|last3=Wall|first3=J. Blake Joseph|last4=Zheng|first4=Michael|last5=Zhou|first5=Yang|last6=Wang|first6=Li|last7=Ruth Vaseghi|first7=Haley|last8=Qian|first8=Li|last9=Liu|first9=Jiandong|title=Systematic comparison of 2A peptides for cloning multi-genes in a polycistronic vector|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=7|issue=1|pages=2193|year=2017|issn=2045-2322|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-02460-2|pmid=28526819|pmc=5438344}}</ref><ref name=\"KarunaSudipto2010\">{{cite book|author1=Sampath Karuna|author2=Roy Sudipto|title=Live Imaging In Zebrafish: Insights Into Development And Disease|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H7LFCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA51|date=30 August 2010|publisher=World Scientific|isbn=978-981-4464-89-5|pages=51\u201352}}</ref>\n\nThe members of 2A peptides are named after the virus in which they have been first described. For example, F2A, the first described 2A peptide, is derived from [[foot-and-mouth disease virus]]. The name \"2A\" itself comes from a [[polyprotein]] in foot-and-mouth disease virus.<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\"/>\n\n==Members==\nFour members of 2A peptides family are frequently used in life science research. They are P2A, E2A, F2A and T2A. F2A is derived from [[foot-and-mouth disease virus]] 18; E2A is derived from equine rhinitis A virus; P2A is derived from [[porcine teschovirus]]-1 2A; T2A is derived from thosea asigna virus 2A.<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\"/>\n\nThe following table shows the sequences of four members of 2A peptides. Adding the sequence \u201c[[Glycine|G]][[Serine|S]][[Glycine|G]]\u201d (Gly-Ser-Gly) on the N-terminal of a 2A peptide is optional.<ref name=\"Szymczak-WorkmanVignali2012\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Sequence\n|-\n| T2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG)    EGRGSLL TCGDVEENPGP}}\n|-\n| P2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG)    ATNFSLLKQAGDVEENPGP}}\n|-\n| E2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG)   QCTNYALLKLAGDVESNPGP}}\n|-\n| F2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG) VKQTLNFDLLKLAGDVESNPGP}}\n|}\n\n==Description==\nThe 2A-peptide-mediated cleavage commences after the [[Translation (biology)|translation]]. The cleavage is trigged by breaking of [[peptide bond]] between the [[Proline]] (P) and [[Glycine]] (G) in C-terminal of 2A peptide. The exact molecular mechanism of 2A-peptide-mediated cleavage is still unknown.<ref name=\"WangWang2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Wang|first1=Yuancheng|last2=Wang|first2=Feng|last3=Wang|first3=Riyuan|last4=Zhao|first4=Ping|last5=Xia|first5=Qingyou|title=2A self-cleaving peptide-based multi-gene expression system in the silkworm Bombyx mori|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=5|issue=1|pages=16273|year=2015|issn=2045-2322|doi=10.1038/srep16273|pmid=26537835|pmc=4633692}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/ryanlab/page2.htm|title=Cleavage Activity of Aphtho- and Cardiovirus 2A Oligopeptidic Sequences.|publisher=University of St Andrews|access-date=2019-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230094902/http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/ryanlab/page2.htm|archive-date=2016-12-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, it is believed to involve ribosomal \"skipping\" of glycyl-prolyl peptide bond formation rather than true proteolytic cleavage.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ryan |first1=Martin D. |last2=Mehrotra |first2=Amit |last3=Gani |first3=David |last4=Donnelly |first4=Michelle L. L. |last5=Hughes |first5=Lorraine E. |last6=Luke |first6=Garry |last7=Li |first7=Xuejun |title=Analysis of the aphthovirus 2A/2B polyprotein 'cleavage' mechanism indicates not a proteolytic reaction, but a novel translational effect: a putative ribosomal 'skip' |journal=Journal of General Virology |date=1 May 2001 |volume=82 |issue=5 |pages=1013\u20131025 |doi=10.1099/0022-1317-82-5-1013 |pmid=11297676 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sharma |first1=Pamila |last2=Yan |first2=Fu |last3=Doronina |first3=Victoria A. |last4=Escuin-Ordinas |first4=Helena |last5=Ryan |first5=Martin D. |last6=Brown |first6=Jeremy D. |title=2A peptides provide distinct solutions to driving stop-carry on translational recoding |journal=Nucleic Acids Research |date=April 2012 |volume=40 |issue=7 |pages=3143\u20133151 |doi=10.1093/nar/gkr1176 |pmid=22140113 |pmc=3326317 }}</ref>\n\n==Application==\nIn [[genetic engineering]], the 2A peptides are used to cleave a longer peptide into two shorter peptides. The 2A peptides can be applied when the fused protein doesn\u2019t work. Inserting the [[Coding DNA sequence|CDS]] of a 2A peptide into the fusing point or replacing the linker sequence with the CDS of a 2A peptide protein can cleave the fused protein into two separated peptides, making the two peptides to regain the function.<ref name=\"Szymczak-WorkmanVignali2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Szymczak-Workman|first1=A. L.|last2=Vignali|first2=K. M.|last3=Vignali|first3=D. A. A.|title=Design and Construction of 2A Peptide-Linked MulticistronicVectors|journal=Cold Spring Harbor Protocols|volume=2012|issue=2|year=2012|pages=199\u2013204|issn=1559-6095|doi=10.1101/pdb.ip067876|pmid=22301656}}</ref>\n\n2A peptides, when combined with the [[Internal ribosome entry site|IRES]] elements, can make it possible to generate three separated peptides within a single [[Primary transcript|transcript]].<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\"/>\n\n== Incomplete cleavage ==\nDifferent 2A peptides have different efficiencies of self-cleaving, P2A being the most and F2A the least efficient.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Jin Hee|last2=Lee|first2=Sang-Rok|last3=Li|first3=Li-Hua|last4=Park|first4=Hye-Jeong|last5=Park|first5=Jeong-Hoh|last6=Lee|first6=Kwang Youl|last7=Kim|first7=Myeong-Kyu|last8=Shin|first8=Boo Ahn|last9=Choi|first9=Seok-Yong|date=2011-04-29|editor-last=Thiel|editor-first=Volker|title=High Cleavage Efficiency of a 2A Peptide Derived from Porcine Teschovirus-1 in Human Cell Lines, Zebrafish and Mice|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=6|issue=4|pages=e18556|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0018556|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3084703|pmid=21602908}}</ref> Therefore, up to 50% of F2A-linked proteins can remain in the cell as a [[fusion protein]], which might cause some unpredictable outcomes, including a gain of function.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Velychko|first=Sergiy|last2=Kang|first2=Kyuree|last3=Kim|first3=Sung Min|last4=Kwak|first4=Tae Hwan|last5=Kim|first5=Kee-Pyo|last6=Park|first6=Chanhyeok|last7=Hong|first7=Kwonho|last8=Chung|first8=ChiHye|last9=Hyun|first9=Jung Keun|date=April 2019|title=Fusion of Reprogramming Factors Alters the Trajectory of Somatic Lineage Conversion|journal=Cell Reports|volume=27|issue=1|pages=30\u201339.e4|doi=10.1016/j.celrep.2019.03.023|pmid=30943410}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Internal ribosome entry site|IRES]]\n*[[Recombinant DNA]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Genetic engineering]]\n[[Category:Molecular biology]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:2A peptide Working Mechanism.jpg|thumb|An illustration of 2A peptide function: when the [[Coding DNA sequence|CDS]] of a 2A peptide is inserted between two CDSs of protein, the peptide will be cleaved into two proteins folding independently.]]\n'''2A self-cleaving peptides''', or '''2A peptides''', is a class of 18\u201322 [[amino acid|aa]]-long peptides, which can induce the cleaving of the [[recombinant protein]] in cell. 2A peptides are derived from the 2A region in the [[genome]] of [[virus]]es.<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\">{{cite journal|last1=Liu|first1=Ziqing|last2=Chen|first2=Olivia|last3=Wall|first3=J. Blake Joseph|last4=Zheng|first4=Michael|last5=Zhou|first5=Yang|last6=Wang|first6=Li|last7=Ruth Vaseghi|first7=Haley|last8=Qian|first8=Li|last9=Liu|first9=Jiandong|title=Systematic comparison of 2A peptides for cloning multi-genes in a polycistronic vector|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=7|issue=1|pages=2193|year=2017|issn=2045-2322|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-02460-2|pmid=28526819|pmc=5438344}}</ref><ref name=\"KarunaSudipto2010\">{{cite book|author1=Sampath Karuna|author2=Roy Sudipto|title=Live Imaging In Zebrafish: Insights Into Development And Disease|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H7LFCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA51|date=30 August 2010|publisher=World Scientific|isbn=978-981-4464-89-5|pages=51\u201352}}</ref>\n\nThe members of 2A peptides are named after the virus in which they have been first described. For example, F2A, the first described 2A peptide, is derived from [[foot-and-mouth disease virus]]. The name \"2A\" itself comes from a [[polyprotein]] in foot-and-mouth disease virus.<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\"/>\n\n==Members==\nFour members of 2A peptides family are frequently used in life science research. They are P2A, E2A, F2A and T2A. F2A is derived from [[foot-and-mouth disease virus]] 18; E2A is derived from equine rhinitis A virus; P2A is derived from [[porcine teschovirus]]-1 2A; T2A is derived from thosea asigna virus 2A.<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\"/>\n\nThe following table shows the sequences of four members of 2A peptides. Adding the sequence \u201c[[Glycine|G]][[Serine|S]][[Glycine|G]]\u201d (Gly-Ser-Gly) on the N-terminal of a 2A peptide is optional.<ref name=\"Szymczak-WorkmanVignali2012\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Sequence\n|-\n| T2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG)     EGRGSLLTCGDVEENPGP}}\n|-\n| P2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG)    ATNFSLLKQAGDVEENPGP}}\n|-\n| E2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG)   QCTNYALLKLAGDVESNPGP}}\n|-\n| F2A || style=\"white-space: pre-wrap\" | {{mono|(GSG) VKQTLNFDLLKLAGDVESNPGP}}\n|}\n\n==Description==\nThe 2A-peptide-mediated cleavage commences after the [[Translation (biology)|translation]]. The cleavage is trigged by breaking of [[peptide bond]] between the [[Proline]] (P) and [[Glycine]] (G) in C-terminal of 2A peptide. The exact molecular mechanism of 2A-peptide-mediated cleavage is still unknown.<ref name=\"WangWang2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Wang|first1=Yuancheng|last2=Wang|first2=Feng|last3=Wang|first3=Riyuan|last4=Zhao|first4=Ping|last5=Xia|first5=Qingyou|title=2A self-cleaving peptide-based multi-gene expression system in the silkworm Bombyx mori|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=5|issue=1|pages=16273|year=2015|issn=2045-2322|doi=10.1038/srep16273|pmid=26537835|pmc=4633692}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/ryanlab/page2.htm|title=Cleavage Activity of Aphtho- and Cardiovirus 2A Oligopeptidic Sequences.|publisher=University of St Andrews|access-date=2019-01-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230094902/http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/ryanlab/page2.htm|archive-date=2016-12-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, it is believed to involve ribosomal \"skipping\" of glycyl-prolyl peptide bond formation rather than true proteolytic cleavage.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ryan |first1=Martin D. |last2=Mehrotra |first2=Amit |last3=Gani |first3=David |last4=Donnelly |first4=Michelle L. L. |last5=Hughes |first5=Lorraine E. |last6=Luke |first6=Garry |last7=Li |first7=Xuejun |title=Analysis of the aphthovirus 2A/2B polyprotein 'cleavage' mechanism indicates not a proteolytic reaction, but a novel translational effect: a putative ribosomal 'skip' |journal=Journal of General Virology |date=1 May 2001 |volume=82 |issue=5 |pages=1013\u20131025 |doi=10.1099/0022-1317-82-5-1013 |pmid=11297676 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sharma |first1=Pamila |last2=Yan |first2=Fu |last3=Doronina |first3=Victoria A. |last4=Escuin-Ordinas |first4=Helena |last5=Ryan |first5=Martin D. |last6=Brown |first6=Jeremy D. |title=2A peptides provide distinct solutions to driving stop-carry on translational recoding |journal=Nucleic Acids Research |date=April 2012 |volume=40 |issue=7 |pages=3143\u20133151 |doi=10.1093/nar/gkr1176 |pmid=22140113 |pmc=3326317 }}</ref>\n\n==Application==\nIn [[genetic engineering]], the 2A peptides are used to cleave a longer peptide into two shorter peptides. The 2A peptides can be applied when the fused protein doesn\u2019t work. Inserting the [[Coding DNA sequence|CDS]] of a 2A peptide into the fusing point or replacing the linker sequence with the CDS of a 2A peptide protein can cleave the fused protein into two separated peptides, making the two peptides to regain the function.<ref name=\"Szymczak-WorkmanVignali2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Szymczak-Workman|first1=A. L.|last2=Vignali|first2=K. M.|last3=Vignali|first3=D. A. A.|title=Design and Construction of 2A Peptide-Linked MulticistronicVectors|journal=Cold Spring Harbor Protocols|volume=2012|issue=2|year=2012|pages=199\u2013204|issn=1559-6095|doi=10.1101/pdb.ip067876|pmid=22301656}}</ref>\n\n2A peptides, when combined with the [[Internal ribosome entry site|IRES]] elements, can make it possible to generate three separated peptides within a single [[Primary transcript|transcript]].<ref name=\"LiuChen2017\"/>\n\n== Incomplete cleavage ==\nDifferent 2A peptides have different efficiencies of self-cleaving, P2A being the most and F2A the least efficient.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Jin Hee|last2=Lee|first2=Sang-Rok|last3=Li|first3=Li-Hua|last4=Park|first4=Hye-Jeong|last5=Park|first5=Jeong-Hoh|last6=Lee|first6=Kwang Youl|last7=Kim|first7=Myeong-Kyu|last8=Shin|first8=Boo Ahn|last9=Choi|first9=Seok-Yong|date=2011-04-29|editor-last=Thiel|editor-first=Volker|title=High Cleavage Efficiency of a 2A Peptide Derived from Porcine Teschovirus-1 in Human Cell Lines, Zebrafish and Mice|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=6|issue=4|pages=e18556|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0018556|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3084703|pmid=21602908}}</ref> Therefore, up to 50% of F2A-linked proteins can remain in the cell as a [[fusion protein]], which might cause some unpredictable outcomes, including a gain of function.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Velychko|first=Sergiy|last2=Kang|first2=Kyuree|last3=Kim|first3=Sung Min|last4=Kwak|first4=Tae Hwan|last5=Kim|first5=Kee-Pyo|last6=Park|first6=Chanhyeok|last7=Hong|first7=Kwonho|last8=Chung|first8=ChiHye|last9=Hyun|first9=Jung Keun|date=April 2019|title=Fusion of Reprogramming Factors Alters the Trajectory of Somatic Lineage Conversion|journal=Cell Reports|volume=27|issue=1|pages=30\u201339.e4|doi=10.1016/j.celrep.2019.03.023|pmid=30943410}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Internal ribosome entry site|IRES]]\n*[[Recombinant DNA]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Genetic engineering]]\n[[Category:Molecular biology]]\n", "name_user": "Artoria2e5", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMembers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2A_self-cleaving_peptides"}
{"title_page": "Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Prince's Company of Riflemen\n| native_name = Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince\n| image = Coat of Arms of Carabiniers du prince.svg\n| image_size = 150px\n| caption = Patch of the Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince\n| dates = 8 December 1817 \u2013 present\n| country = {{flag|Monaco}}\n| branch = ''[[Force Publique (Monaco)|Force Publique]]''\n| type = [[Foot Guards]], and [[Gendarmerie]]\n| role = [[Close Protection]]\n| size = One company, 119 personal<ref name=autogenerated8>{{cite web|url=http://www.gouv.mc/Gouvernement-et-Institutions/Le-Gouvernement/Departement-de-l-Interieur/Compagnie-des-Carabiniers-du-Prince|title=Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince  / D\u00e9partement de l'Int\u00e9rieur / Le Gouvernement / Gouvernement et Institutions / Portail du Gouvernement -  Monaco|first=Gouvernement Princier de|last=Monaco|website=www.gouv.mc|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n| garrison = [[Moneghetti]]<ref name=autogenerated3 /><!-- Commanders -->\n| commander1 = [[Albert II of Monaco|Prince Albert II of Monaco]]\n| commander1_label = Chief Commander\n| commander2 = [[Colonel]] Luc Fringant<ref group=\"note\">The Senior Commander heads the ''[[Force Publique (Monaco)|Force Publique]]''; the military oversight agency.</ref><ref name=Commanders>[https://www.palais.mc/en/sovereign-house/palace-administration-1-23.html Palace administration]</ref>\n| commander2_label = Senior Commander\n| commander3 = [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Philippe Rebaudengo<ref name=Commanders/>\n| commander3_label = Company Commander\n| notable_commanders = \n| nickname = <!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol = Red over White\n| identification_symbol_label = Plume\n| motto = ''\"Honour, loyalty, devotion\"''\n| colors = \n| march = \n| mascot = \n| battles = [[French Revolutionary Wars]],<br>[[Monegasque Revolution]],<br>[[World War I]],<br>[[World War II]],<br>[[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|T\u014dhoku Disaster]]<ref group=\"note\">An eleven man peacekeeping and rescue force was deployed, however, the majority were [[Corps des Sapeurs-Pompiers|Sapeurs-Pompiers]].</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince''' ([[Monarchy of Monaco|Prince's]] [[Company (military unit)|Company]] of [[Rifleman|Riflemen]]) is the [[Infantry]] branch of the ''[[Force Publique (Monaco)|Force Publique]]'',<ref name=autogenerated12>{{cite web|url=http://cloud.gouv.mc/webweb/Annuoff.nsf/%28ListCh%29/739BA04DF7376FD5C12571F50030E6AA!OpenDocument|title=Force Publique - Annuaire Officiel|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> and one of the limited number of [[List of militaries that recruit foreigners|militaries that recruits foreigners]].<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Although [[Monaco|Monaco's]] defence is the responsibility of [[France]],<ref name=\"monaco\">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-02-27 |url=http://www.monaco-consulate.com/news_1024.htm |title=Monaco signs new treaty with France |publisher=Monaco Consulate |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021034944/http://www.monaco-consulate.com/news_1024.htm |archivedate=2007-10-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Monaco maintains a small force for the protection of the [[Sovereign of Monaco|Sovereign]] and the [[Prince's Palace of Monaco|Prince's Palace]].<ref name=autogenerated10 /> Formed by [[Honor\u00e9 IV, Prince of Monaco|Prince Honor\u00e9 IV]] in 1817, the unit was re-organized in 1909.<ref name=autogenerated13>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-02-27 |url=http://www.monaco-consulate.com/news_1024.htm |title=Monaco signs new treaty with france |publisher=Monaco Consulate |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021034944/http://www.monaco-consulate.com/news_1024.htm |archivedate=2007-10-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The company numbers 119 officers and men. Whilst the [[non-commissioned officer|NCOs]] and soldiers are local, the officers have served in the [[French Army]] or the [[Republican Guard (France)|Republican Guard]]. Along with the ''[[Corps des Sapeurs-Pompiers]]'', the Carabiniers form Monaco's total public forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gouv.mc/Gouvernement-et-Institutions/Le-Gouvernement/Departement-de-l-Interieur/Corps-des-Sapeurs-pompiers|title=Corps des Sapeurs-pompiers  / D\u00e9partement de l'Int\u00e9rieur / Le Gouvernement / Gouvernement et Institutions / Portail du Gouvernement -  Monaco|first=Gouvernement Princier de|last=Monaco|website=www.gouv.mc|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Monaco-military-02.JPG|170px|thumb|left|Carabinier at the [[Prince's Palace of Monaco|Prince's Palace]] in [[Monaco-Ville]].]]\n\nAn antecedent of the Carabiniers was the company known in the 19th century as the \"Papalins\", former soldiers of the [[Papal States]], who, upon the destitution of the Papacy's temporal authority at the time of the [[Italian Unification]], were given the role of protecting the [[Sovereign of Monaco|Sovereign]] and the [[House of Grimaldi|Princely Family]]. A road in [[Fontvieille, Monaco|Fontvieille]] is named in honour of them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?hl=en&safe=off&q=Avenue+des+Papalins,+Fontvieille,+Monaco&ie=UTF-8&hq=&hnear=0x12cdc2930c83e8bb:0x19a504b08c003b09,Avenue+des+Papalins,+Monaco&gl=us&ei=RPjkUPCLBeHs0QHEiYGADA&ved=0CDAQ8gEwAA|title=Google Maps|website=Google Maps|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Monaco, the ''Milice Nationale'' was created in 1865.<ref name=autogenerated14>[http://www.pompiers.gouv.mc/321/wwwnew.nsf/1909$/db4c6e6016593114c1257163004604b2fr?OpenDocument&1Fr History of the Corps des Sapeurs-Pompiers and Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812025216/http://www.pompiers.gouv.mc/321/wwwnew.nsf/1909%24/db4c6e6016593114c1257163004604b2fr?OpenDocument&1Fr |date=August 12, 2013 }}</ref> In 1870, the ''Milice Nationale'' was renamed the ''Gardes du Prince'', although, the \"Gardes\" were still tasked with fire-fighting, and national security.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> On May 5, 1881, the ''Gardes du Prince'' were renamed the ''Compagnie de Sapeurs-Pompiers'' to better adjust to their fire-fighting duties.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> On June 17, 1909, the fire-fighting unit was re-organised into a separate operating company called the ''Compagnie de Sapeurs-Pompiers'', while the protection unit was renamed the ''Corps des Carabiniers du Prince''.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> This lasted over 60 years, until the companies were finally renamed the ''[[Corps des Sapeurs-Pompiers]]'', and the ''Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince'', and were placed under the ''[[Force Publique (Monaco)|Force Publique's]]'' direct control.<ref name=autogenerated14 />\n\nThe Carabiniers are currently commanded by [[Military of Monaco#Rank and Insignia|Comdt.]] Philippe Rebaudengo, who was sworn in on February 1, 2007.<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref group=\"note\">The [[Prince of Monaco]] who holds the rank of [[Military of Monaco#Rank and Insignia|Colonel]] is the Commander in Chief.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monte-carlo.mc/en/general/prince-albert-II/|title=His Serene Highness Prince Albert II - Monaco Monte-Carlo|first=|last=Monte-Carlo|website=Monte-Carlo.mc|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> Previous commanders include, [[Military of Monaco#Rank and Insignia|Lt. Col.]] Jacques Morandon (2005-2007), [[Military of Monaco#Rank and Insignia|Lt. Col.]] Luc Fringant (1993-2005), and [[Military of Monaco#Rank and Insignia|Comdt.]] Maurice Allent (1978-1993).<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==Organisation and expenditures==\n\nComposed of 119 personnel of [[Francophone]] nationality (3 officers, 19 non-commissioned officers, and 97 men of rank), the Carabiniers are split into the following divisions:<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref name=autogenerated10>{{cite web|url=http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/francais/maison-souveraine/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers-de-s-a-s-le-prince.70.html|title=Palais Princier de Monaco|first=Palais Princier de|last=Monaco|website=www.palais.mc|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n* Band;\n* Diving Team;\n* Motorcycle Platoon;\n* Bodyguard Unit;\n* Palace Guard;  \n* Honour Guard;\n* [[Civil defence|Civil Defence]].\n\nThe 2012-2013 stating salary for a ''[[Private (rank)|Carabinier]]'' is [[\u20acuro|\u20ac]]2,200 ([[$US|$]]2,908) a month or [[\u20acuro|\u20ac]]26,400 ([[$US|$]]34,893) a year.<ref name=autogenerated9>{{cite web|url=http://www.carrefoursemploi.org/minisites4/paris2012/popupentreprise.php?identreprise=13465|title=popupadhe 3|website=www.carrefoursemploi.org|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> While the Company's 2012-2013 budget is [[\u20acuro|\u20ac]]6.7 million ([[$US|$]]8.8 million) per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conseil-national.mc/admin/rapport_loi/1349247620.pdf|title=2012-2013 National Budget|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105174650/http://www.conseil-national.mc/admin/rapport_loi/1349247620.pdf|archivedate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Duties and missions==\n{{Location map many | Monaco\n| width = 170\n| float = left\n| caption = <center>Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince - Barracks.</center>\n| label = <small>Barracks - Moneghetti</small>\n  | mark = fire.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  | pos = left\n  | bg = \n  | lat_deg = 43.7364961 | lat_min = \n  | lon_deg = 7.4180066 | lon_min = \n| label2 = <small>Palais Princier - Monaco-Ville</small>\n  | mark2 = fire.svg\n  | mark2size = 8\n  | pos2 = left\n  | bg2 = \n  | lat2_deg = 43.7310355 | lat2_min = \n  | lon2_deg = 7.4214448 | lon2_min = \n}}\n\nSince its inception, the Carabiniers were tasked with guarding the [[Prince's Palace of Monaco|Prince's Palace]], ensuring the security of the [[Sovereign of Monaco|Sovereign]] and the [[House of Grimaldi|Princely Family]], to provide services to honour, and to assist [[Law enforcement in Monaco|law enforcement]] in times of need.<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref name=autogenerated10 /><ref name=autogenerated11>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qQfY7uIiC30|title=La Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince de Monaco recrute...|first=|last=chartrestw|date=15 March 2010|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> The Palace is guarded at all times, twenty-four hours a day, with two non-commissioned officers of varying rank, one ''[[Mar\u00e9chal des logis]]'', and eight ''[[Private (rank)|Carabinier]]s''.<ref name=autogenerated10 /> The Changing of the Guard, is performed daily at 11.55 am, and announced by a musical element (two drums, two trumpets).<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\nThe Carabiniers provides services of honour. To \"requisition\", the Company escorts judiciary, participates in official ceremonies, civil and religious, and ceremonial parades and processions.<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref name=autogenerated10 /><ref name=autogenerated11 />\n\nThe Carabiniers also perform various missions of public service. With the creation of a ''Military Aid Unit'', the Carabiniers implement ambulances for the ''[[Monegasque Red Cross]]''.<ref name=autogenerated10 /> The Company participate as such, the security of major sporting events or arts that take place in the Principality, requiring emergency supplies and evacuation.<ref name=autogenerated10 /> The Company participate as appropriate in the implementation of emergency plan, ''ORMOS Red Plan'' (Monaco relief organisation), which also includes the ''[[Corps des Sapeurs-Pompiers]]'', and the ''[[Law enforcement in Monaco|Direction de la S\u00fbret\u00e9 Publique]]''.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\nThe ''Diving Team'' is regularly asked to integrate with security devices, and participate in various rescue missions during the sailing competitions in Monegasque waters. They also participate in scientific observations, underwater environment for the study of pollution in the [[Mediterranean]].<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref name=autogenerated10 /><ref name=autogenerated11 />\n\nA ''Motorcycle Platoon'' is responsible for the [[Prince of Monaco|Prince]] on his daily schedule, and escorting sovereign heads of state visiting Monaco.<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n==The Band==\n{{Main|Prince\u2019s Band of Carabiniers}}\n[[File:Mon\u00e9gasque Military Drummer.jpeg|thumb|A drummer of the band.]]\nThe Carabiniers maintain a musical band consisting of twenty-six \"rifle-musicians\" under the command of a ''[[Sergeant|Mar\u00e9chal des Logis Chef]]''.<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/english/sovereign-house/the-palace-guards/the-palace-guards.453.html|title=Palais Princier de Monaco|first=Palais Princier de|last=Monaco|website=www.palais.mc|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423061945/http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/english/sovereign-house/the-palace-guards/the-palace-guards.453.html|archivedate=23 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated7>[http://www.monacowealthmanagement.com/article.php?sm=mon&m=roy&id=12&PHPSESSID=58693e0d61b5faa57d7e7d808dd73b9a ::: Monaco Wealth Management :::<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 1978, the title of \"''Fanfare de la Companies des Carabiniers''\" was adopted.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://madmonarchist.blogspot.com/2009/07/royal-guardians-profile-princes-company.html|title=The Mad Monarchist: Royal Guardians Profile: The Prince's Company of Carabiniers|first=|last=Madmonarchist|date=7 July 2009|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> An integral part of the unit, the band is not trained solely to perform music. Instead, Carabiniers receive the same training as their comrades.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The band participates in the same occasions, and duties as the Company.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The diversity of the repertoire of the band allows it to perform at official ceremonies, sporting events, and public concerts.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref name=autogenerated7 /> Since 1989, the band has performed outside of Monaco, in multitudes of destinations, such as: [[Saumur]], [[N\u00eemes]], [[Albertville]], [[Lugano]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[Turin]], [[Lisbon]], [[Seville]], [[Geneva]], and [[Hanover]].<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==Dress and equipment==\n\nThe equipment and vehicles of the Carabiniers have been upgraded in recent years. Mobility has been improved by the adoption of modern vehicles, adapted to different missions, such as two [[Piranha V|MOWAG Piranha V]]s, six [[Peugeot P4]]s, and seven [[BMW R1200RT-P]]s.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Old rifles and revolvers have been replaced by firearms such as the [[M16A2 rifle|M16A2]], and [[Glock 17]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nicematin.com/diaporama/monaco-dans-les-coulisses-avec-les-carabiniers-du-prince-albert-ii.621348.html?idx=4|title=Monaco: dans les coulisses avec les carabiniers du Prince Albert II|website=www.nicematin.com|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-701167?ref=feeds%2Foncnn|title=Recession? What Recession? - CNN iReport<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101074135/http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-701167?ref=feeds%2Foncnn|archivedate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freeriders2.over-blog.com/article-la-releve-de-la-garde-sur-the-rock-102936508.html|title=LA RELEVE DE LA GARDE SUR &quot;THE ROCK&quot; -   le blog freeriders2|first=|last=BIKER06|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nParade dress in the winter is a modernised version of that worn in the early 1900s. It comprises a dark blue tunic, and light blue trousers with red facings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cache.daylife.com/imageserve/0cjw0nY8nS5em/610x.jpg|title=Whiter Uniform<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130319005327/http://cache.daylife.com/imageserve/0cjw0nY8nS5em/610x.jpg|archivedate=19 March 2013}}</ref> A medium-blue cloth helmet is worn, with plumes for gala occasions. White trefoil [[epaulettes]], [[spats (footwear)|spats]] and [[aiguillettes]] date from the 19th century. In the summer a simple white shirt sleeve order is worn with a white helmet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Guard_Prince%27s_palace_Monaco.JPG/220px-Guard_Prince%27s_palace_Monaco.JPG|title=Summer Uniform<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> For ordinary duties a modern police style uniform is worn with a peaked cap replacing the helmet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/35/Monaco-military-01.JPG/180px-Monaco-military-01.JPG|title=Ordinary Duties Uniform<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325084543/http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/35/Monaco-military-01.JPG/180px-Monaco-military-01.JPG|archivedate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Vehicles==\n<!--READ FIRST: This section is for cited entries only. Please do not add entries into this list without a citation from a reliable source. All entries without a citation will be removed. Thank you.--> \n[[File:Renault Master police Monaco.JPG|170px|thumb|[[Law enforcement in Monaco|Police]] version of the [[Renault Master]] in [[Monaco-Ville]].]]\n[[File:Sc\u00e9nic de la police mon\u00e9gasque.JPG|170px|thumb|[[Law enforcement in Monaco|Police]] version of the [[Renault Scenic]] in [[La Condamine]].]]\n[[Image:Iowa-800.jpg|170px|thumb|[[BMW R60]] in 1967.]]\n\n===Current===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Vehicle\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Country of origin \n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Type\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|In service ([[Circa|ca]].)\t\n! sty