16 rifle#M4 carbine|M4A1]], M16A4.]]\n[[File:Glock 17C cropped.jpg|thumb|170px|[[Glock 17]].]]\n[[File:Fass57-diag.jpg|thumb|170px|[[SIG SG 510]].]]\n\n===Current===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Weapon\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Country of origin \n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Type\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|In service ([[Circa|ca]].)\t\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Notes\n|-\n| [[Glock 17]]\n| {{flag|Austria}}\n| [[Semi-automatic pistol]]\n| 100\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated1 />\n|-\n| [[Beretta 92]]\n| {{flag|Italy}}\n| [[Semi-automatic pistol]]\n| 12\n| <ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[SIG P210]]\n| {{flag|Switzerland}}\n| [[Semi-automatic pistol]]\n| 12<ref group=\"note\">Originally 12 pistols were used, however, many pistols have been permanently retired.</ref>\n| <ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[M16A2 rifle|M16A2]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| [[Assault rifle]]\n| 100\n| <ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated1 />\n|-\n| [[M16 rifle#M4 carbine|M4A1]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| [[Assault rifle]]\n| 12\n| <ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated1 />\n|-\n| [[SIG SG 510]]\n| {{flag|Switzerland}}\n| [[Battle rifle]]\n| 80<ref group=\"note\">Originally 80 rifles were used, however, many rifles have been permanently retired.</ref>\n| <ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[FN MAG]]\n| {{flag|Belgium}}\n| [[General-purpose machine gun]]\n| 6 \n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[Lance-grenade individuel Mle F1 (LGI Mle F1)|LGI Mle F1]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Rocket-propelled grenade]]\n| 3\n| <ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n|}\n<ref group=\"note\" name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Former===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Weapon\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Country of origin \n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Type\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|In service ([[Circa|ca]].)\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Notes\n|-\n| [[Chassepot|Fusil mod\u00e8le 1866]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Bolt-action rifle]]\n| 70\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[Remington Rolling Block rifle]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| [[Rolling block]]\n| 60\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[Fusil Gras mle 1874|Fusil Gras Mod\u00e8le 1874 M80]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Bolt-action rifle]]\n| 60\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[MAS 1873 revolver|Mod\u00e8le 1874 Revolver]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Service Pistol|Service Revolver]]\n| 110\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[Lebel Model 1886 rifle|Fusil Mle 1886 M93]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Bolt-action rifle]]\n| 80\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[Mod\u00e8le 1892 revolver|Mod\u00e8le 1892 Revolver]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Service Pistol|Service Revolver]]\n| 100\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[MAS-36 rifle|MAS Mod\u00e8le 36]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Bolt-action rifle]]\n| 80\n| <ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n| [[MAS-49 rifle|MAS Mod\u00e8le 49]]\n| {{flag|France}}\n| [[Semi-automatic rifle]]\n| 110\n|<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|-\n|}\n<ref group=\"note\" name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Recruitment==\n[[File:Guard Prince's palace Monaco.JPG|170px|thumb|Carabinier at the [[Prince's Palace of Monaco|Prince's Palace]] in [[Monaco-Ville]].]]\nCarabiniers are recruited from among candidates who meet the following conditions:<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/francais/maison-souveraine/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers/faire-carriere-dans-les-carabiniers-du-prince.321.html|title=Palais Princier de Monaco|first=Palais Princier de|last=Monaco|website=www.palais.mc|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019162856/http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/francais/maison-souveraine/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers/faire-carriere-dans-les-carabiniers-du-prince.321.html|archivedate=19 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated9 />\n\n* Male;\n* Between twenty and thirty-years-old;\n* Single (marriage licence granted after the confirmation period);\n* [[Francophone]];\n* Pass a [[Eye examination|vision examination]];\n* Within a minimum height of 1.8&nbsp;m (5.9&nbsp;ft) to a maximum height of 2&nbsp;m (6.6&nbsp;ft);\n* [[Body mass index|BMI]] (Body Mass Index) less than or equal to twenty-five;\n* Pass a physical fitness test and examination;\n* Graduated with a high school or equivalent degree;\n* Possess a driving licence;\n* Capable of swimming.\n\nApplicants may be esteemed if they know skills in one or more specialties relevant to the Carabiniers. For instance: music (primarily band instruments), diving, first aid, culinary, computer, and mechanics training, or combat experience.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n==Career development==\n\nAt the time of his enlistment, a Carabinier signs his first contract for five years which is validated after a period of instruction, and confirmation period in which ability and motivation are verified.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> This confirmation is usually after one year's service, but may be extended for one or even two years further probation.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> A Carabinier can pursue his career and commitments by successive reenlistments after each five years of service until reaching age 55, subjecting to meet all the conditions of fitness.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Promotion on merit allows a number of Carabiniers to reach the various grades of noncommissioned officers.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> However, a very low turnover rate of enlistments means that 50% finish their military career as a Carabinier first or second class.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n==Rank insignia==\n\n<div class=\"NavFrame\" style=\"text-align:left\">\n<div class=\"NavHead\" style=\"background:#000000; color: white; padding-bottom:0; text-align:center; padding-left:1em\">Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince Rank Insignia (All ranks in French)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniforminsignia.org/?option=com_insigniasearch&Itemid=53&result=2518|title=Prince's Company of Carabiniers / Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince|website=www.uniforminsignia.org|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref></div>\n<div class=\"NavContent\" style=\"margin-bottom:.5em; padding:.2em\">\n{| class=\"itwiki_template_toc\" style=\"clear:both; margin-top:1em; text-align:center; float:center; border: 1px grey solid; margin: auto; width:100%\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=#000000 border=0 style=\"color: white\"|'''Officer'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\" height=\"100px\"|[[Image:COL-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Colonel]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:LeutCOL-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:COM-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Major|Commandant]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\" height=\"100px\"|[[Image:CAP-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Captain (land)|Capitaine]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:LEUT-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[1st Lieutenant|Lieutenant]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:S.LEUT-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[2nd Lieutenant|Sous Lieutenant]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=#000000 border=0 style=\"color: white\" | '''Non Commissioned Officer (NCO)'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\" height=\"100px\"|[[Image:ASS-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Officer Cadet|Assistant]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:ADJChef-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Chief Warrant Officer|Adjudant Chef]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:ADJ-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Warrant Officer|Adjutant]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\" height=\"100px\"|[[Image:MARMaj-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Sergeant Major|Mar\u00e9chal des Logis Major]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:MARChef-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Sergeant|Mar\u00e9chal des Logis Chef]]\n|colspan=\"2\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:MAR-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Sergeant|Mar\u00e9chal des Logis]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=#000000 border=0 style=\"color: white\" | '''Enlisted'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\" height=\"100px\"|[[Image:BRIG-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Corporal|Brigadier]]\n|colspan=\"3\" width=\"33%\" align=\"center\"|[[Image:CAR-carabiniersMonaco.jpg|50px]]<br>[[Private (rank)|Carabinier]]\n|}\n</div></div>\n\n==Popular culture==\n*''J\u00e9r\u00e9mie Covillault'', portrays a Carabinier in ''[[Grace of Monaco (film)|Grace of Monaco]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2095649/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title=Grace of Monaco (2014)|publisher=|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Daniel Ducruet]] <small>(former Carabinier)</small>\n*[[Th\u00e9ophile Bellando de Castro]] <small>(former Carabinier)</small>\n*[[Force Publique (Monaco)|Force Publique]]\n*[[Corps des Sapeurs-Pompiers]]\n*[[Monaco]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gouv.mc/Gouvernement-et-Institutions/Le-Gouvernement/Departement-de-l-Interieur/Compagnie-des-Carabiniers-du-Prince Compagnie des Carabiniers du Prince - Gouvernement Princier]\n* [http://www.palais.mc/monaco/palais-princier/francais/maison-souveraine/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers/la-compagnie-des-carabiniers-de-s-a-s-le-prince.70.html La Compagnie des Carabiniers de S.A.S. le Prince - Palais Princier]\n\n[[Category:Military of Monaco]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1817]]\n[[Category:Guards regiments]]\n[[Category:Gendarmerie]]\n[[Category:Guards of honour]]\n\n[[lt:Monako karin\u0117s paj\u0117gos]]\n", "name_user": "Snake bgd", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compagnie_des_Carabiniers_du_Prince"}
{"title_page": "Isma'il ibn Ja'far", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Isma'il ibn Ja'far\n| image = (\u0625\u0633\u0645\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0628\u0627\u062c \u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 (\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647.png\n| birth_date = [[Islamic calendar|103 AH]]<br>(approximately 722 C.E)\n| birth_place = [[Medina]]\n| death_date = [[Islamic calendar|138 AH]]<br>(approximately 762 C.E)\n| resting_place = [[Al-Baqi']] [[Madina]] [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| other_names = Abu Muhammad, Isma'il Al-A\"raj\n| known_for = Elder son of [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]], sixth [[Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl\u012b]] [[Im\u0101m]], Syed\n| title = az-Azbab-i-Itlaq (''Absolute lord''), Al-Wafi, Al-aa\"raj\n| predecessor = [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]] According to Isma'ili Shia\n| successor = [[Muhammad ibn Isma'il]] According to Isma'ili Shia\n| children = [[Muhammad ibn Isma'il]], Ali ibn Isma'il, Fatima\n| parents = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]] (father)\n* Fatima bint al-Hussain'l-Athram bin al-[[Hasan bin Ali]] (mother)\n}}\n| relatives = [[Musa al-Kadhim]]\n}}\n{{Ismailis}}\n\n'''Abu Muhammad Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl ibn Ja\u02bffar al-Mub\u0101rak''' ({{lang-ar|\u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631}}; c.719 AD &ndash; c.762 AD) was the eldest son of [[Imamah (Shi'a doctrine)|Imam]] [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]. He is also known as Isma'il Al-\u00c3raj ibn Ja'far (\u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mezan.net/mawsouat/sadek/f06.html|title=\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f ( \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 ) \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645  - \u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0632\u0627\u0646|last=\u0628\u0635\u0648\u062a\u0647|first=\u0645\u0642\u0648\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0641\u0636\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647|website=www.mezan.net|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alzahraa.org/1/Ahl%20Al-bayat/Alsadeq%20AS.htm|title=\u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u064a\u0627\u0632\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0621 \u0633 \u0633\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0623\u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0644\u0627\u0645|website=alzahraa.org|access-date=2017-02-27}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://al-mousa.net/1/8.htm|title=\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645|website=al-mousa.net|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://alsadah.hooxs.com/t4-topic|title=\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628(\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u062a\u0634\u062c\u064a\u0631 \u062a\u062d\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0632\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0648\u0632\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0646\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u0646\u0633\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0626\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0637\u0647\u0627\u0631)|work=alsadah.hooxs.com|access-date=2017-02-27|language=ar}}</ref> Following Ja'far's death, the Shia community split between those who believed the Imamate was passed to [[Musa al-Kazim|Musa ibn Ja'far]], who would become the [[Twelver Shia]], and those who believed that the Imamate passed to Isma'il ibn Ja'far, who would become the [[Isma'ili]] branch named after Isma'il.<ref name=\"Hollister1979\">{{cite book|author=John Norman Hollister|title=The Shi'a of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NmwwAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=8 February 2011|year=1979|publisher=Oriental Books Reprint Corp. : [exclusively distributed by Munshiram Manoharla]}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIsma'il was born in [[Shawwal]] 100 AH/719 AD He was the eldest son of Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq. His mother, Fatima bint al-Hussain'l-Athram bin al-[[Hasan bin Ali]], was the first wife of [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]. He was the brother of [[Abdullah al-Aftah ibn Ja'far al-Sadiq|Abdullah al-Aftah]].\n\nIsma'ili sources say that, after the age of seven, as his father's designated successor, Isma'il was kept apart from his siblings, limited in his contact with the public, with his father taking personal responsibility for his education. Given his father's reputation as a scholar and the number of distinguished students who sought out his tuition, Isma'il would have received excellent training. It is said that whenever Ja'far was ill and unable to fulfill his duties as Imam, he deputized Isma'il, although his role was restricted to the confines of the home.\n\nAccording to Daftary, Isma'il may have taken part in an anti-Abbasid plot in 755 and identified with the more activist, or militant Shi'a (some of whom split off as the Zaydis). He may have been summoned to the Caliph's court with others to face charges but was spared execution, unlike some of his fellow plotters.{{citation needed|date=March 2017|reason=there were attached citation numbers without refs}}\n\nTo protect him from persecution, his father sent him into hiding and publicly declared him deceased. The majority Twelver groups argue that Isma'il actually died during his father's Imamate in the year 138 AH/756 AD.\n\nIn about 762, Isma'il may have left Medina for Basra, although this is disputed. He is said to have had a full grasp of the esoteric truth, the inner message of Islam. He was succeeded by his son, Muhammad, as the 8th Isma'ili Imam, who was about 22 at the time. Some Isma'ilis believe that Muhammad bin Isma'il became \"hidden\" and will return as the Mahdi, to establish universal peace and justice.\n\nAccording to Daftary, Isma'il may have led a revolt against the Abbasids in 815, \"and died shortly afterwards\" in [[Medina]].{{citation needed|date=March 2017|reason=attached citation number without ref}} He probably lived in \"southwestern Persia ... from where he dispatched his own Dais to adjoining areas\".{{citation needed|date=March 2017|reason=attached citation number without ref}}\n\n==Burial place==\nAccording to some Isma'ili sources,  Isma'il ibn Ja'far is buried in [[Salamiyah]], a city located in [[Syria]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://ismailignosis.com/2014/10/02/who-succeeded-imam-jafar-al-sadiq-seven-proofs-for-the-imamat-of-imam-ismail-ibn-jafar/|title=Who Succeeded Imam Jafar al-Sadiq? Seven Proofs for the Imamat of Imam Ismail ibn Jafar|last=Gnostic|first=Ismaili|website=Ismaili Gnosis|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref> Other sources point to Al-Baqi' Madina as his burial place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawoodi-bohras.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=1207|title=Burial  Places of Imams - Dawoodi Bohra Forum|website=www.dawoodi-bohras.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref> [[Twelver]] Shia's and [[Sunni Muslims]] sources have contradicted this, stating that he was buried in [[Al-Baqi']] [[Medina]], the holy Islamic city located in [[Hijaz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jafariyanews.com/2k11_news/sep/7mausavi_8shawwal_msg.htm|title=Criminal silence on the Baqee destruction reason behind Muslim problems; Moosavi on 8 Shawwal {{!}} Jafariya News Network|website=www.jafariyanews.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ziaraat.org/madina/ismail_bin_jafar.php|title=Ziarat of Hazrat Ismail bin Imam Jafar Sadiq (as)|website=ziaraat.org|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ziaraat.org/places/saudi.php|title=SAUDI ARABIA - ZIARAAT & INFORMATION|website=www.ziaraat.org|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://almiskeenah.com/AlMadinahAlMunawwarah/madinah-a-munawwarah/page/4|title=Madinah a-Munawwarah {{!}} almiskeenah {{!}} Page 4|website=almiskeenah.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.duas.org/baqee.htm|title=History of Baqi cemetry in Medina|website=www.duas.org|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://seattleclouds.com/myapplications/aqenterprises/VisitingMadinahShareef/page09.html|title=iClassic|website=seattleclouds.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==The Isma'ili\u2013Twelver schism==\nThe Isma'ili\u2013Twelver split occurred during and after Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq's lifetime. It was initially thought that Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq's elder son, Isma'il ibn Ja'far (either first or second eldest to his first wife, Fatima bint al-Hussain).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dawoodi-bohras.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=7646|title=6th Imam Molana Ismail a.s. bin Imam Jaffer Sadik a.s. - Dawoodi Bohra Forum|website=dawoodi-bohras.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>Al-Hasan ibn Musa al-Nawbakhti. ''Kitab Firaq al-Shia''. Tr. by Abbas Kadhim, Shi'a Sects 2007, p. 123.</ref> would be the next Imam, arguably found in both Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b and Twelver sources.<ref name=\"IsmailiGnosis20141002\">{{cite web |title=Who Succeeded Imam Jafar Al-Sadiq? Seven Proofs for the Imamat of Imam Ismail ibn Jafar |url=https://ismailignosis.com/2014/10/02/who-succeeded-imam-jafar-al-sadiq-seven-proofs-for-the-imamat-of-imam-ismail-ibn-jafar/ |date=2 October 2014 |website=Ismaili Gnosis |access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> However, his untimely death prior to Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq's death, led to multiple splits and theories within the community.<ref>Al-Hasan ibn Musa al-Nawbakhti. ''Kitab Firaq al-Shia''. Tr. by Abbas Kadhim, Shi'a Sects 2007, p. 122-142.</ref>\n\nWhat came to be known as Isma'ilis, are those who believed that the Imamate should remain within the line of Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far. It was believed that the designation went to Isma'il ibn Ja'far, and therefore the Imamate should continue through his lineage.<ref>{{cite web |last=Badrijanab |title=6th Imam Molana Ismail A.s. Bin Imam Jaffer Sadik A.s. |url=http://www.dawoodi-bohras.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=7646 |date=15 June 2012 |website=Dawoodi Bohra Forum |access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IsmailiGnosis20141002\" /> His early supporters initially theorized that Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far\u2019s death was staged, and he went into hiding out of fear for his life from the Abbasid Caliph al-Mans\u016br.<ref>Al-Hasan ibn Musa al-Nawbakhti. ''Kitab Firaq al-Shia''. Tr. by Abbas Kadhim, Shi'a Sects 2007, p. 123.</ref><ref>P. W. Ivanow, Ismaili ''Tradition Concerning the Rise of the Fatimids'', 1941, p. 275-278</ref> They refused to acknowledge his death, and some even claimed to have seen him after his funeral. However, most Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs later accepted Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far\u2019s death, and instead followed his son Muhammad ibn Isma'il as the next Imam, since the Imamate could still be continued through Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far\u2019s lineage. On a theological level, Ismai'lis refuse to acknowledge Imams outside of the lineage of Ismail ibn Ja\u2019far due to the notion of ''na\u1e63\u1e63'' (designation) and ''\u2018i\u0219ma'' (infallibility). Because Shi\u2019as believe that the Imams are infallible and contain special knowledge of the Divine decree, it is inconceivable that Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq would have incorrectly chosen Imam Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far as his successor and then retract his original ''na\u1e63\u1e63''. This would mean that Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq either made a major mistake which would make him fallible, or later claims regarding other designations were forged narrations. \n\nIthna-'Asharis, following the early death of Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far acknowledged the designation of Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq\u2019s younger son, M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im, from his slave-wife, \u1e24am\u012bda al-Barbariyya. Various hadith reports from the Twelver Shi\u2019i collection contain narrations about the designation of Imam M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im, along with his exceptional character and wisdom from an early age.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imam Musa b. Ja'far al-Kazim (a): Imamate |url=http://en.wikishia.net/view/Imam_Musa_b._Ja%27far_al-Kazim_(a)#Imamate |website=[[WikiShia]] |access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref> Witnesses include some of Imam Jafar al-Sadiq\u2019s sons, \u2018Ali and Is\u1e25\u0101q, who affirmed M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im\u2019s na\u1e63\u1e63.<ref>Shaykh al-Mufid. ''Kitab al-Irshad''. Translated by Seyyid Hossein Nasr, p. 407</ref> Other arguments made for Imam M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im include the passing down of special objects that belonged to the Prophet, \u2018Ali and Fatima to the designated Imams.<ref>Shaykh al-Mufid. ''Kitab al-Irshad''. Translated by Seyyid Hossein Nasr, p. 408</ref> While the early followers (later Twelvers) of Imam Jafar al-Sadiq believed that Isma'il ibn Ja'far might have been the Imam due to his beloved status by his father, some argue that he was neither explicitly designated, nor meant to be, due to his early death.  Another mainstream view also purports a \u201cchange\u201d or \u201cabrogation\u201d in the Divine Decree, known as ''bad\u0101\u2019'', in which God may abrogate a previous decree for something better.<ref>Ayoub, Mahmoud. Divine Preordination and Human Hope a Study of the Concept of Bad\u0101\u02be in Im\u0101m\u012b Sh\u012b\u02bf\u012b Tradition. Journal of the American Oriental Society, Vol. 106, No. 4 (Oct. - Dec., 1986), pp. 623632. P 624</ref>  As a result, Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq\u2019s infallibility is not called into question.  The Ithna-\u2018Asharis continued to follow the Imamate from M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im\u2019s lineage until their twelfth Imam went into Occultation. They await their twelfth Imam as the final Mahdi.\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center |boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Isma'il ibn Jafar'''\n|2= 2. [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]\n|3= 3. Fatimah bint Husayn  \n|4= 4. [[Muhammad al-Baqir]]\n|5= 5. [[Umm Farwah bint al-Qasim]]\n|6= 6. Husayn al-Athram \n|7= 7. Unnamed daughter\n|8= 8. [[Ali ibn Husayn Zayn al-Abidin]]\n|9= 9. [[Fatimah bint Hasan]]  \n|10= 10. [[Qasim ibn Muhammad ibn Abu Bakr|Al-Qasim ibn Muhammad]]\n|11= 11. Asma bint [[Abdul-Rahman ibn Abi Bakr|Abdul-Rahman]]\n|12= 12. [[Hasan ibn Ali]] \n|14= 14. Umar ibn [[Ali]]  \n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Ismaili imams]]\n* [[Family tree of Muhammad#Family tree linking prophets to Imams ]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-hou|branch=Clan|name='''Isma'il ibn Jafar'''<br>of the [[Ahl al-Bayt]]|[[Banu Hashim]]|[[Islamic calendar|122 AH]]|[[Approximation|\u2248]] 719 [[AD]]|[[Islamic calendar|\u2026. AH]]|[[Approximation|\u2248]] 762\u2026. [[AD]]|[[Quraysh (sura)|Quraish]]}} \n{{S-rel|sh}}\n{{S-bef|before = [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title = 7th [[Imamah (Shi'a Ismaili doctrine)|Imam]] of [[Ismailism]]|years 755 \u2013(815)\u2026..AD/138-\u2026.AH}}\n{{S-aft|after =[[Muhammad ibn Isma'il|Muhammad ibn Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl ash-Sh\u0101kir]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ismail ibn Jafar}}\n[[Category:722 births]]\n[[Category:755 deaths]]\n[[Category:Family of Muhammad]]\n[[Category:Ismaili imams]]\n[[Category:Shia Islam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Isma'il ibn Ja'far\n| image = (\u0625\u0633\u0645\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0628\u0627\u062c \u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 (\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647.png\n| birth_date = [[Islamic calendar|103 AH]]<br>(approximately 722 C.E)\n| birth_place = [[Medina]]\n| death_date = [[Islamic calendar|138 AH]]<br>(approximately 762 C.E)\n| resting_place = [[Al-Baqi']] [[Madina]] [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| other_names = Abu Muhammad, Isma'il Al-A\"raj\n| known_for = Elder son of [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]], sixth [[Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl\u012b]] [[Im\u0101m]], Syed\n| title = az-Azbab-i-Itlaq (''Absolute lord''), Al-Wafi, Al-aa\"raj\n| predecessor = [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]] According to Isma'ili Shia\n| successor = [[Muhammad ibn Isma'il]] According to Isma'ili Shia\n| children = [[Muhammad ibn Isma'il]], Ali ibn Isma'il, Fatima\n| parents = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]] (father)\n* Fatima bint al-Hussain'l-Athram bin al-[[Hasan bin Ali]] (mother)\n}}\n| relatives = [[Musa al-Kadhim]]\n}}\n{{Ismailis}}\n\n'''Abu Muhammad Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl ibn Ja\u02bffar al-Mub\u0101rak''' ({{lang-ar|\u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631}}; c. born: 719 AD, [[Medina]] - died circa 762 AD, [[Medina]]) was the eldest son of [[Imamah (Shi'a doctrine)|Imam]] [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]. He is also known as Isma'il Al-\u00c3raj ibn Ja'far (\u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mezan.net/mawsouat/sadek/f06.html|title=\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f ( \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 ) \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645  - \u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0632\u0627\u0646|last=\u0628\u0635\u0648\u062a\u0647|first=\u0645\u0642\u0648\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0641\u0636\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647|website=www.mezan.net|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alzahraa.org/1/Ahl%20Al-bayat/Alsadeq%20AS.htm|title=\u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u064a\u0627\u0632\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0621 \u0633 \u0633\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0623\u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0640\u0644\u0627\u0645|website=alzahraa.org|access-date=2017-02-27}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://al-mousa.net/1/8.htm|title=\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062c\u0639\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0627\u062f\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645|website=al-mousa.net|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://alsadah.hooxs.com/t4-topic|title=\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628(\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0648\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u062a\u0634\u062c\u064a\u0631 \u062a\u062d\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0632\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0648\u0632\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0646\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u0646\u0633\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0626\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0637\u0647\u0627\u0631)|work=alsadah.hooxs.com|access-date=2017-02-27|language=ar}}</ref> Following Ja'far's death, the Shia community split between those who believed the Imamate was passed to [[Musa al-Kazim|Musa ibn Ja'far]], who would become the [[Twelver Shia]], and those who believed that the Imamate passed to Isma'il ibn Ja'far, who would become the [[Isma'ili]] branch named after Isma'il.<ref name=\"Hollister1979\">{{cite book|author=John Norman Hollister|title=The Shi'a of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NmwwAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=8 February 2011|year=1979|publisher=Oriental Books Reprint Corp. : [exclusively distributed by Munshiram Manoharla]}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nIsma'il was born in [[Shawwal]] 100 AH/719 AD He was the eldest son of Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq. His mother, Fatima bint al-Hussain'l-Athram bin al-[[Hasan bin Ali]], was the first wife of [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]. He was the brother of [[Abdullah al-Aftah ibn Ja'far al-Sadiq|Abdullah al-Aftah]].\n\nIsma'ili sources say that, after the age of seven, as his father's designated successor, Isma'il was kept apart from his siblings, limited in his contact with the public, with his father taking personal responsibility for his education. Given his father's reputation as a scholar and the number of distinguished students who sought out his tuition, Isma'il would have received excellent training. It is said that whenever Ja'far was ill and unable to fulfill his duties as Imam, he deputized Isma'il, although his role was restricted to the confines of the home.\n\nAccording to Daftary, Isma'il may have taken part in an anti-Abbasid plot in 755 and identified with the more activist, or militant Shi'a (some of whom split off as the Zaydis). He may have been summoned to the Caliph's court with others to face charges but was spared execution, unlike some of his fellow plotters.{{citation needed|date=March 2017|reason=there were attached citation numbers without refs}}\n\nTo protect him from persecution, his father sent him into hiding and publicly declared him deceased. The majority Twelver groups argue that Isma'il actually died during his father's Imamate in the year 138 AH/756 AD.\n\nIn about 762, Isma'il may have left Medina for Basra, although this is disputed. He is said to have had a full grasp of the esoteric truth, the inner message of Islam. He was succeeded by his son, Muhammad, as the 8th Isma'ili Imam, who was about 22 at the time. Some Isma'ilis believe that Muhammad bin Isma'il became \"hidden\" and will return as the Mahdi, to establish universal peace and justice.\n\nAccording to Daftary, Isma'il may have led a revolt against the Abbasids in 815, \"and died shortly afterwards\".{{citation needed|date=March 2017|reason=attached citation number without ref}} He probably lived in \"southwestern Persia ... from where he dispatched his own Dais to adjoining areas\".{{citation needed|date=March 2017|reason=attached citation number without ref}}\n\n==Burial place==\nAccording to some Isma'ili sources,  Isma'il ibn Ja'far is buried in [[Salamiyah]], a city located in [[Syria]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://ismailignosis.com/2014/10/02/who-succeeded-imam-jafar-al-sadiq-seven-proofs-for-the-imamat-of-imam-ismail-ibn-jafar/|title=Who Succeeded Imam Jafar al-Sadiq? Seven Proofs for the Imamat of Imam Ismail ibn Jafar|last=Gnostic|first=Ismaili|website=Ismaili Gnosis|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref> Other sources point to Al-Baqi' Madina as his burial place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dawoodi-bohras.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=1207|title=Burial  Places of Imams - Dawoodi Bohra Forum|website=www.dawoodi-bohras.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref> [[Twelver]] Shia's and [[Sunni Muslims]] sources have contradicted this, stating that he was buried in [[Al-Baqi']] [[Medina]], the holy Islamic city located in [[Hijaz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jafariyanews.com/2k11_news/sep/7mausavi_8shawwal_msg.htm|title=Criminal silence on the Baqee destruction reason behind Muslim problems; Moosavi on 8 Shawwal {{!}} Jafariya News Network|website=www.jafariyanews.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ziaraat.org/madina/ismail_bin_jafar.php|title=Ziarat of Hazrat Ismail bin Imam Jafar Sadiq (as)|website=ziaraat.org|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ziaraat.org/places/saudi.php|title=SAUDI ARABIA - ZIARAAT & INFORMATION|website=www.ziaraat.org|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://almiskeenah.com/AlMadinahAlMunawwarah/madinah-a-munawwarah/page/4|title=Madinah a-Munawwarah {{!}} almiskeenah {{!}} Page 4|website=almiskeenah.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.duas.org/baqee.htm|title=History of Baqi cemetry in Medina|website=www.duas.org|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://seattleclouds.com/myapplications/aqenterprises/VisitingMadinahShareef/page09.html|title=iClassic|website=seattleclouds.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==The Isma'ili\u2013Twelver schism==\nThe Isma'ili\u2013Twelver split occurred during and after Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq's lifetime. It was initially thought that Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq's elder son, Isma'il ibn Ja'far (either first or second eldest to his first wife, Fatima bint al-Hussain).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dawoodi-bohras.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=7646|title=6th Imam Molana Ismail a.s. bin Imam Jaffer Sadik a.s. - Dawoodi Bohra Forum|website=dawoodi-bohras.com|access-date=2016-04-11}}</ref><ref>Al-Hasan ibn Musa al-Nawbakhti. ''Kitab Firaq al-Shia''. Tr. by Abbas Kadhim, Shi'a Sects 2007, p. 123.</ref> would be the next Imam, arguably found in both Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012b and Twelver sources.<ref name=\"IsmailiGnosis20141002\">{{cite web |title=Who Succeeded Imam Jafar Al-Sadiq? Seven Proofs for the Imamat of Imam Ismail ibn Jafar |url=https://ismailignosis.com/2014/10/02/who-succeeded-imam-jafar-al-sadiq-seven-proofs-for-the-imamat-of-imam-ismail-ibn-jafar/ |date=2 October 2014 |website=Ismaili Gnosis |access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> However, his untimely death prior to Imam Ja'far al-Sadiq's death, led to multiple splits and theories within the community.<ref>Al-Hasan ibn Musa al-Nawbakhti. ''Kitab Firaq al-Shia''. Tr. by Abbas Kadhim, Shi'a Sects 2007, p. 122-142.</ref>\n\nWhat came to be known as Isma'ilis, are those who believed that the Imamate should remain within the line of Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far. It was believed that the designation went to Isma'il ibn Ja'far, and therefore the Imamate should continue through his lineage.<ref>{{cite web |last=Badrijanab |title=6th Imam Molana Ismail A.s. Bin Imam Jaffer Sadik A.s. |url=http://www.dawoodi-bohras.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=7646 |date=15 June 2012 |website=Dawoodi Bohra Forum |access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IsmailiGnosis20141002\" /> His early supporters initially theorized that Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far\u2019s death was staged, and he went into hiding out of fear for his life from the Abbasid Caliph al-Mans\u016br.<ref>Al-Hasan ibn Musa al-Nawbakhti. ''Kitab Firaq al-Shia''. Tr. by Abbas Kadhim, Shi'a Sects 2007, p. 123.</ref><ref>P. W. Ivanow, Ismaili ''Tradition Concerning the Rise of the Fatimids'', 1941, p. 275-278</ref> They refused to acknowledge his death, and some even claimed to have seen him after his funeral. However, most Ism\u0101'\u012bl\u012bs later accepted Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far\u2019s death, and instead followed his son Muhammad ibn Isma'il as the next Imam, since the Imamate could still be continued through Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far\u2019s lineage. On a theological level, Ismai'lis refuse to acknowledge Imams outside of the lineage of Ismail ibn Ja\u2019far due to the notion of ''na\u1e63\u1e63'' (designation) and ''\u2018i\u0219ma'' (infallibility). Because Shi\u2019as believe that the Imams are infallible and contain special knowledge of the Divine decree, it is inconceivable that Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq would have incorrectly chosen Imam Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far as his successor and then retract his original ''na\u1e63\u1e63''. This would mean that Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq either made a major mistake which would make him fallible, or later claims regarding other designations were forged narrations. \n\nIthna-'Asharis, following the early death of Isma'il ibn Ja\u2019far acknowledged the designation of Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq\u2019s younger son, M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im, from his slave-wife, \u1e24am\u012bda al-Barbariyya. Various hadith reports from the Twelver Shi\u2019i collection contain narrations about the designation of Imam M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im, along with his exceptional character and wisdom from an early age.<ref>{{cite web |title=Imam Musa b. Ja'far al-Kazim (a): Imamate |url=http://en.wikishia.net/view/Imam_Musa_b._Ja%27far_al-Kazim_(a)#Imamate |website=[[WikiShia]] |access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref> Witnesses include some of Imam Jafar al-Sadiq\u2019s sons, \u2018Ali and Is\u1e25\u0101q, who affirmed M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im\u2019s na\u1e63\u1e63.<ref>Shaykh al-Mufid. ''Kitab al-Irshad''. Translated by Seyyid Hossein Nasr, p. 407</ref> Other arguments made for Imam M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im include the passing down of special objects that belonged to the Prophet, \u2018Ali and Fatima to the designated Imams.<ref>Shaykh al-Mufid. ''Kitab al-Irshad''. Translated by Seyyid Hossein Nasr, p. 408</ref> While the early followers (later Twelvers) of Imam Jafar al-Sadiq believed that Isma'il ibn Ja'far might have been the Imam due to his beloved status by his father, some argue that he was neither explicitly designated, nor meant to be, due to his early death.  Another mainstream view also purports a \u201cchange\u201d or \u201cabrogation\u201d in the Divine Decree, known as ''bad\u0101\u2019'', in which God may abrogate a previous decree for something better.<ref>Ayoub, Mahmoud. Divine Preordination and Human Hope a Study of the Concept of Bad\u0101\u02be in Im\u0101m\u012b Sh\u012b\u02bf\u012b Tradition. Journal of the American Oriental Society, Vol. 106, No. 4 (Oct. - Dec., 1986), pp. 623632. P 624</ref>  As a result, Imam Ja'far al-S\u0101diq\u2019s infallibility is not called into question.  The Ithna-\u2018Asharis continued to follow the Imamate from M\u016bs\u0101 al-K\u0101\u1e93im\u2019s lineage until their twelfth Imam went into Occultation. They await their twelfth Imam as the final Mahdi.\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center |boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Isma'il ibn Jafar'''\n|2= 2. [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]\n|3= 3. Fatimah bint Husayn  \n|4= 4. [[Muhammad al-Baqir]]\n|5= 5. [[Umm Farwah bint al-Qasim]]\n|6= 6. Husayn al-Athram \n|7= 7. Unnamed daughter\n|8= 8. [[Ali ibn Husayn Zayn al-Abidin]]\n|9= 9. [[Fatimah bint Hasan]]  \n|10= 10. [[Qasim ibn Muhammad ibn Abu Bakr|Al-Qasim ibn Muhammad]]\n|11= 11. Asma bint [[Abdul-Rahman ibn Abi Bakr|Abdul-Rahman]]\n|12= 12. [[Hasan ibn Ali]] \n|14= 14. Umar ibn [[Ali]]  \n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Ismaili imams]]\n* [[Family tree of Muhammad#Family tree linking prophets to Imams ]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-hou|branch=Clan|name='''Isma'il ibn Jafar'''<br>of the [[Ahl al-Bayt]]|[[Banu Hashim]]|[[Islamic calendar|122 AH]]|[[Approximation|\u2248]] 719 [[AD]]|[[Islamic calendar|\u2026. AH]]|[[Approximation|\u2248]] 762\u2026. [[AD]]|[[Quraysh (sura)|Quraish]]}} \n{{S-rel|sh}}\n{{S-bef|before = [[Ja'far al-Sadiq]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title = 7th [[Imamah (Shi'a Ismaili doctrine)|Imam]] of [[Ismailism]]|years 755 \u2013(815)\u2026..AD/138-\u2026.AH}}\n{{S-aft|after =[[Muhammad ibn Isma'il|Muhammad ibn Ism\u0101\u02bf\u012bl ash-Sh\u0101kir]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ismail ibn Jafar}}\n[[Category:722 births]]\n[[Category:755 deaths]]\n[[Category:Family of Muhammad]]\n[[Category:Ismaili imams]]\n[[Category:Shia Islam]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "bring intro into line with bio standards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isma%27il_ibn_Ja%27far"}
